00:02:52.881 --> 00:02:55.130
So I'm going to tell you a
little bit today about what

00:02:55.130 --> 00:02:57.590
our research group is focused
on-- broadly on restoring

00:02:57.590 --> 00:02:59.219
the American dream.

00:02:59.219 --> 00:03:01.760
And I'm going to talk about how,
in our own local communities

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:03.176
and our local
institutions, we can

00:03:03.176 --> 00:03:05.690
make a big difference on
issues like inequality

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:07.130
and economic opportunity.

00:03:07.130 --> 00:03:09.770
But I want to start at a
much bigger picture level,

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:11.720
by talking about
the American dream.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:14.660
Which, of course, is a
multifaceted, complicated

00:03:14.660 --> 00:03:17.510
concept that means different
things to different people.

00:03:17.510 --> 00:03:19.490
But I want to distill
it to a statistic

00:03:19.490 --> 00:03:21.400
that we can measure
systematically

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:23.900
in the data, which is a way
that the American dream has been

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:25.550
traditionally conceptualized.

00:03:25.550 --> 00:03:28.820
The idea that through hard
work, any child in America

00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:30.614
should have the
chance of going on

00:03:30.614 --> 00:03:32.780
to have a higher living
standard than their parents,

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:34.940
or going on to earn
more than their parents.

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:37.520
And so what we're starting
out with in this first chart

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:39.440
is just an assessment
of whether that's

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:43.220
true in the United States today,
and how the American dream has

00:03:43.220 --> 00:03:44.340
fared over time.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:47.150
So what we're doing here is
calculating, very simply,

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:50.390
the fraction of kids who go on
to earn more than their parents

00:03:50.390 --> 00:03:53.910
did, based on the year
in which they're born.

00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:58.040
So as you can see here, for kids
born in the 1940s and 1950s,

00:03:58.040 --> 00:03:59.600
it was a virtual
guarantee that you

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:01.910
were going to achieve the
American dream of moving up,

00:04:01.910 --> 00:04:03.220
relative to your parents.

00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:06.770
92% of kids born in
1940 went on to earn

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:08.400
more than their parents did.

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:10.220
If you look at what
has happened over time,

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:13.490
you see a very stark fading
of the American dream.

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:15.570
Such that, as
Jacqueline mentioned,

00:04:15.570 --> 00:04:18.649
for kids born in the 1980s,
who are turning 30 today,

00:04:18.649 --> 00:04:20.519
when we're measuring
their earnings,

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:22.834
It's essentially a coin
flip-- a 50-50 shot--

00:04:22.834 --> 00:04:25.250
as to whether you're going to
do better than your parents.

00:04:25.250 --> 00:04:27.140
Now this broad
trend, I think, is

00:04:27.140 --> 00:04:28.700
not just of economic interest.

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:31.389
I think it's a fundamental
social and political interest

00:04:31.389 --> 00:04:32.930
in the United States,
because I think

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.150
it underlies a lot
of the frustration

00:04:35.150 --> 00:04:37.010
that people around the
US are expressing--

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:41.280
that the US is no longer a land
of opportunity, as it once was.

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:43.970
So motivated by that trend,
in our research group,

00:04:43.970 --> 00:04:47.360
Opportunity Insights,
based at Harvard,

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:49.700
we're essentially trying
to tackle the big picture

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:52.340
question of, how can we
restore the American dream?

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:54.500
What is driving that trend?

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:57.904
And our approach has, really,
three central elements.

00:04:57.904 --> 00:05:00.320
The first, which will be very
familiar to all of you here,

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:03.320
is that we try to harness
large data sets, typically

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:06.380
structured data coming from
government data sources--

00:05:06.380 --> 00:05:09.320
census data, tax data,
things like that--

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:11.650
in order to study how to
increase upward mobility.

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:14.090
And I think this is
really a special moment

00:05:14.090 --> 00:05:16.610
in social science where, much
as you all are using data

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:20.090
in your work to improve the
products that people have

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:22.840
access to, I think our
knowledge of social science

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:26.840
is going to be revolutionized
by modern big data in the coming

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:28.160
decades.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:32.217
Second, we focus greatly,
as Jacqueline mentioned,

00:05:32.217 --> 00:05:34.550
on not just doing this research,
but trying to translate

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:36.710
that research to policy change.

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:39.230
By trying to inform
public conversations,

00:05:39.230 --> 00:05:42.200
or as I'll give you a couple
of examples of, increasingly

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:44.900
partnering with local
government agencies, colleges,

00:05:44.900 --> 00:05:48.950
other institutions, to really
create change on the ground.

00:05:48.950 --> 00:05:51.620
The third point,
kind of a departure

00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:53.150
for what I'm going
to show you, is

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:55.010
that rather than
approaching the data

00:05:55.010 --> 00:05:57.300
at an aggregate
or national level,

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:00.200
we really try to hone in on
specific geographic areas

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:02.210
or specific subgroups,
to try to understand

00:06:02.210 --> 00:06:04.980
what the drivers of inequality
and opportunity are.

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:06.629
And so the starting
point for what

00:06:06.629 --> 00:06:08.420
I'm going to talk about
today is that there

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:12.320
are very sharp local differences
in rates of upward mobility

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:15.800
that I think should shape how we
think about the broader problem

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:17.494
of the fading American dream.

00:06:17.494 --> 00:06:19.160
And so I'm going to
start by showing you

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:21.352
that data with this map here.

00:06:21.352 --> 00:06:23.060
It's just to give you
a bit of background

00:06:23.060 --> 00:06:24.410
before I describe what it shows.

00:06:24.410 --> 00:06:28.580
We construct this map using
data following 20 million kids

00:06:28.580 --> 00:06:29.840
from birth to adulthood.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:33.530
That's using anonymized
information from tax returns

00:06:33.530 --> 00:06:36.530
connected to census records,
where we basically tracked

00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:38.810
these 20 million kids--
essentially all kids born

00:06:38.810 --> 00:06:40.600
in America in the early 1980s--

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:43.160
follow them to adulthood,
and look at how they ended up

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:46.610
doing in terms of their earnings
conditional on growing up

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:48.000
in a low income family.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.570
And so what we're doing in
this map is taking that data

00:06:50.570 --> 00:06:54.740
and assigning kids to locations
based on where they grew up.

00:06:54.740 --> 00:06:57.980
We divide the US into
740 different metro

00:06:57.980 --> 00:06:59.180
and rural areas.

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:00.950
And in each of those
areas we take the set

00:07:00.950 --> 00:07:03.700
of kids who grew up there in
low income families-- that

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:05.960
is families of the 25th
percentile of the income

00:07:05.960 --> 00:07:09.410
distribution, earning
about $25,000 a year.

00:07:09.410 --> 00:07:11.660
We follow those kids
into adulthood and ask,

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:14.350
how much do the kids who grew
up in each of these places

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:15.777
earn, on average, in adulthood?

00:07:15.777 --> 00:07:17.360
So think of this as
a way of measuring

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:20.550
how upward mobility varies
across areas in the United

00:07:20.550 --> 00:07:22.070
States.

00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:25.010
And so the map is colored
such that blue areas,

00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:26.630
like in the center
of the country,

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:29.420
represent areas with higher
levels of upward mobility,

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:32.150
and red colors represent
areas with lower levels

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:33.420
of upward mobility.

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:36.870
So start by just looking at
the scale in the lower right.

00:07:36.870 --> 00:07:39.680
You can see that there's a
dramatic range in kids' chances

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:41.900
of moving up across
the United States,

00:07:41.900 --> 00:07:43.530
depending upon
where they grow up.

00:07:43.530 --> 00:07:45.510
In the darkest red
colors, you see

00:07:45.510 --> 00:07:48.660
that kids who grow up in
families earning about $25,000

00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:52.792
a year, their own incomes,
on average, are about $27,000

00:07:52.792 --> 00:07:55.000
a year in adulthood-- like
in a place like Charlotte,

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:56.760
North Carolina, for example.

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:58.410
In contrast, if you
look at the center

00:07:58.410 --> 00:08:00.990
of the country, or a place like
Salt Lake City, for instance,

00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:06.060
or some areas on the coasts,
you see numbers like 45,000.

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:09.120
Kids starting out in families
earning $25,000 a year

00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:12.730
are, on average, ending up
earning about $45,000 a year.

00:08:12.730 --> 00:08:16.080
So there's a very
broad spectrum in terms

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:18.780
of rates of upward mobility
within the United States.

00:08:18.780 --> 00:08:22.290
That aggregate national picture
that I started out with really

00:08:22.290 --> 00:08:25.950
is driven by a great
heterogeneity across areas.

00:08:25.950 --> 00:08:29.400
Now naturally, the question of
interest to us as academics,

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:32.220
and to policymakers, is
to ask what is driving

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:33.809
this variation across areas.

00:08:33.809 --> 00:08:35.309
And what, ultimately,
might we be

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:38.789
able to do to increase
upward mobility in places,

00:08:38.789 --> 00:08:40.380
or for subgroups,
where we currently

00:08:40.380 --> 00:08:42.720
have less economic opportunity.

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:45.450
One thing I'd like
to point out on that

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:47.976
is that one of the first
explanations that might come

00:08:47.976 --> 00:08:49.350
to your mind is
maybe differences

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:51.420
in upward mobility
across places are

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:53.370
driven by differences
in the types of jobs

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:56.800
that people have access to,
or things like developments

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:59.070
in technology, and so forth.

00:08:59.070 --> 00:09:02.139
As you can see from this map,
though, that doesn't entirely

00:09:02.139 --> 00:09:03.055
appear to be the case.

00:09:03.055 --> 00:09:03.555
Right?

00:09:03.555 --> 00:09:05.764
So if you take an example
like Charlotte, some of you

00:09:05.764 --> 00:09:07.471
might know that
Charlotte, North Carolina

00:09:07.471 --> 00:09:09.810
is one of the most rapidly
growing cities in the United

00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:10.310
States.

00:09:10.310 --> 00:09:12.450
It's had one of the
highest rates of job growth

00:09:12.450 --> 00:09:14.580
over the past 20 or 25 years.

00:09:14.580 --> 00:09:16.530
Yet, as you can
see here, Charlotte

00:09:16.530 --> 00:09:19.110
is one of the places in America
with the very lowest levels

00:09:19.110 --> 00:09:21.630
of upward mobility, among
big cities, for the kids

00:09:21.630 --> 00:09:22.720
who grow up there.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:23.850
So how does that add up?

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:26.310
How can you both
have very high job

00:09:26.310 --> 00:09:29.320
and wage growth, and have
very low upward mobility?

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:31.230
So what's happening in
places like Charlotte,

00:09:31.230 --> 00:09:33.840
or Atlanta, or a number of
other high-growth cities

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:36.300
is that they basically
import talent.

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:38.730
Lots of people move to
Charlotte, move to Atlanta

00:09:38.730 --> 00:09:41.310
to get those high paying jobs,
but they don't necessarily

00:09:41.310 --> 00:09:42.030
grow up there.

00:09:42.030 --> 00:09:46.380
And it's not always the case
that high job growth benefits

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:48.030
the local residents--
something we

00:09:48.030 --> 00:09:49.480
see in many different contexts.

00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:51.780
This is one example of that.

00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:54.690
Now, in this big map,
your eye naturally

00:09:54.690 --> 00:09:56.910
gravitates to the broad
regional variation.

00:09:56.910 --> 00:09:59.490
Places like the Midwest look
better for upward mobility

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:02.970
than the southeast, or places
in the industrial Midwest--

00:10:02.970 --> 00:10:04.750
like Cleveland, and so forth.

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:06.300
But what is striking,
and what we've

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:08.460
been focusing on
more recently in work

00:10:08.460 --> 00:10:10.440
that we released a
couple of months ago,

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:14.010
is that there's substantial
variation-- not just regionally

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:16.740
across the country,
but even within cities

00:10:16.740 --> 00:10:18.940
at very small geographies.

00:10:18.940 --> 00:10:21.960
So to illustrate that, I'm
going to turn and flip over

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:24.720
to this tool that
we've developed, called

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:28.770
the Opportunity Atlas,
which you can access and--

00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:29.820
sorry, if we can just--

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:31.974
there we go.

00:10:31.974 --> 00:10:34.140
So you can access this you
know freely by just going

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:38.160
to opprotunityatlas.org,
and type in any address--

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:41.340
very much like a Google map--

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:42.770
and zoom in to any area.

00:10:42.770 --> 00:10:45.300
So I'm starting out with the
map that I just showed you,

00:10:45.300 --> 00:10:46.260
at a national level.

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:48.870
And now I'm going to zoom
in-- given local interest

00:10:48.870 --> 00:10:50.970
here-- to the Bay
Area, and show you

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:58.530
the same data now, at a census
tract level in the Bay Area.

00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:00.780
So census tracts are--

00:11:03.975 --> 00:11:07.370
there's 70,000 census
tracts in the United States,

00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:09.840
and each of them have
about 4,000 people.

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:11.520
So to give you a sense
of scale, a place

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:14.130
like Palo Alto is
itself divided into 17

00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:16.570
different neighborhoods, and
what we're showing you here.

00:11:16.570 --> 00:11:18.690
So this is a very
fine-grained information.

00:11:18.690 --> 00:11:20.550
Same statistic that
I started out with,

00:11:20.550 --> 00:11:24.120
take low income kids
growing up in each place,

00:11:24.120 --> 00:11:26.885
and essentially calculate their
average incomes in adulthood.

00:11:26.885 --> 00:11:29.010
There's some statistical
details in the background,

00:11:29.010 --> 00:11:32.500
but that that's basically
what we're doing here.

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:35.010
And so the first thing I'd
like you to see on this map

00:11:35.010 --> 00:11:36.870
is, if you look at
the Bay Area, you

00:11:36.870 --> 00:11:39.974
see the same spectrum of
colors that I showed you

00:11:39.974 --> 00:11:40.890
at the national level.

00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:41.100
Right?

00:11:41.100 --> 00:11:42.900
So you can go from
a place that looks

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:45.267
like Alabama or
Charlotte, in terms

00:11:45.267 --> 00:11:47.100
of rates of upward
mobility, to a place that

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:50.670
looks like Iowa, within a few
miles within the Bay Area.

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:53.062
Now some of the
broad patterns here

00:11:53.062 --> 00:11:54.270
will strike you as intuitive.

00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:57.360
So you see, for instance,
that the peninsula, much

00:11:57.360 --> 00:11:59.970
of San Francisco, has higher
rates of upward mobility

00:11:59.970 --> 00:12:02.670
than parts of the East Bay--
in particular, Oakland.

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:04.260
Right?

00:12:04.260 --> 00:12:08.704
But let me now zoom in further
to discuss this variation

00:12:08.704 --> 00:12:09.870
in a little bit more detail.

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:12.420
In particular, to the areas
where we have large low income

00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:15.420
populations-- in Oakland
and surrounding areas--

00:12:15.420 --> 00:12:18.750
to show you how you can pick
out more granular variation

00:12:18.750 --> 00:12:22.720
that I think illustrates some
of what might be going on here.

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:26.160
So if we look here
in Oakland, you

00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:28.770
see that there's a very
sharp, almost a dividing line

00:12:28.770 --> 00:12:32.430
between Oakland and San Leandro,
where the colors almost trip

00:12:32.430 --> 00:12:35.020
discretely from red to blue.

00:12:35.020 --> 00:12:38.070
So part of that is driven
by something Jacqueline

00:12:38.070 --> 00:12:40.230
alluded to, which is
racial differences

00:12:40.230 --> 00:12:41.337
in economic opportunity.

00:12:41.337 --> 00:12:42.920
So what you can do
with these data is,

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:44.560
not just look at the
data in aggregate,

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:46.500
but look at specific subgroups.

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:49.530
So what I'm going to do
here is click on black,

00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:53.300
to subset the data
to black Americans.

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:57.070
And you can see that some of
that divide is driven by race.

00:12:57.070 --> 00:12:59.400
But even conditional
on race, there

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:01.410
are sharp differences
in Oakland,

00:13:01.410 --> 00:13:02.970
relative to San Leandro.

00:13:02.970 --> 00:13:05.850
So one thing I should
note, just as a side note,

00:13:05.850 --> 00:13:08.480
as you pointed out, even
within a given area,

00:13:08.480 --> 00:13:09.960
there are really
sharp differences

00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:12.600
in rates of upward mobility
between blacks and whites--

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:16.050
and in particular, between
black men and white men.

00:13:16.050 --> 00:13:18.690
If you look at black
women versus white women,

00:13:18.690 --> 00:13:20.860
you see very similar outcomes.

00:13:20.860 --> 00:13:23.760
But in particular, for men, race
plays an extremely important

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:24.930
role.

00:13:24.930 --> 00:13:27.750
And so it's important
to see that even when

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:29.964
you focus on the
black population,

00:13:29.964 --> 00:13:32.130
there's still this substantial
variation across very

00:13:32.130 --> 00:13:33.420
nearby neighborhoods.

00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:35.880
Now if I look
specifically at black men,

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:38.015
where you see some of the
most striking patterns,

00:13:38.015 --> 00:13:38.890
as I was just saying.

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:41.265
And I'm going to look at black
men growing up in the very

00:13:41.265 --> 00:13:43.020
lowest income families.

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:45.570
You see that there are certain
places here, for instance,

00:13:45.570 --> 00:13:48.960
let me click this tract,
which is a neighborhood called

00:13:48.960 --> 00:13:51.150
Fruitvale, in Oakland.

00:13:51.150 --> 00:13:53.070
And you see some really
striking, I think,

00:13:53.070 --> 00:13:55.020
disturbing statistics
about the United States.

00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:59.880
So here you see that for black
men growing up in low income

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:03.420
families in Fruitvale, their
average income in adulthood

00:14:03.420 --> 00:14:05.411
is $5,600.

00:14:05.411 --> 00:14:05.910
Right?

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:07.784
And importantly here,
one thing I should note

00:14:07.784 --> 00:14:10.080
is we're tracking these
men, no matter where

00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:11.216
they live in adulthood.

00:14:11.216 --> 00:14:13.090
So these are people who
grew up in Fruitvale.

00:14:13.090 --> 00:14:14.730
They might not be
living there now.

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:16.410
Might be somewhere
completely different.

00:14:16.410 --> 00:14:18.660
But among the set of
people who grew up there,

00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:21.090
they have an average
income of just $5,600.

00:14:21.090 --> 00:14:22.590
So how is that possible?

00:14:22.590 --> 00:14:24.480
The way you get such
a low average income

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:28.000
is by having lots of people
who are not working at all.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.110
And in particular, what you
can do with these types of data

00:14:31.110 --> 00:14:32.880
is look, not just
add income, but look

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:33.980
at a variety of outcomes.

00:14:33.980 --> 00:14:37.890
So if I click over here now to
look at incarceration rates,

00:14:37.890 --> 00:14:40.240
you see a really
striking statistic,

00:14:40.240 --> 00:14:44.520
which is that 43% of the
black men who grew up

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:46.500
in this particular
neighborhood are

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:48.900
incarcerated on a single day--

00:14:48.900 --> 00:14:52.350
on the date of the 2010 census.

00:14:52.350 --> 00:14:53.929
So if you think
about lifetime odds

00:14:53.929 --> 00:14:56.220
of being incarcerated, growing
up in that neighborhood,

00:14:56.220 --> 00:14:59.280
it's going to look like 60%,
70%, something like that.

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:03.360
Which is how you end up with
an average earnings of $5,600.

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:04.020
Right?

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:07.470
So the point here is that
there's this incredibly

00:15:07.470 --> 00:15:08.670
granular variation.

00:15:08.670 --> 00:15:11.040
At some level you might
react to that by saying,

00:15:11.040 --> 00:15:13.290
I'm shocked by the
magnitudes, that we

00:15:13.290 --> 00:15:16.134
see such adverse
outcomes, but maybe I

00:15:16.134 --> 00:15:18.300
had some sense that there
were parts of Oakland that

00:15:18.300 --> 00:15:19.590
are really tough places--

00:15:19.590 --> 00:15:21.300
high poverty, high crime--

00:15:21.300 --> 00:15:24.500
so qualitatively maybe I'm not
so surprised by that picture.

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:28.080
But what I think is perhaps
much more surprising is,

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:33.180
you can go to places that are
just a few miles south, like

00:15:33.180 --> 00:15:37.410
down here in San Leandro, where
you have rates of incarceration

00:15:37.410 --> 00:15:39.150
that are dramatically lower--

00:15:39.150 --> 00:15:43.940
5% or 1%-- compared to the 40%
that we were seeing in Oakland.

00:15:43.940 --> 00:15:44.440
Right?

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:46.200
And so the point I'm
trying to make here

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:50.370
is that when we think
about economic opportunity

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:52.680
in America, really,
we should be thinking

00:15:52.680 --> 00:15:54.630
at a much more local scale.

00:15:54.630 --> 00:15:57.564
It's not even about the Bay
Area versus other cities.

00:15:57.564 --> 00:15:58.980
It's actually
within the Bay Area,

00:15:58.980 --> 00:16:00.480
and within a few
neighborhoods that

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:02.340
are within a couple of
miles of each other,

00:16:02.340 --> 00:16:05.500
that you see extremely
different outcomes for kids.

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:08.010
And so understanding what's
driving that variation,

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:10.800
in our view, can
potentially provide a path

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:14.370
to figuring out how you increase
opportunity more broadly.

00:16:14.370 --> 00:16:17.190
So let me now,
with that example,

00:16:17.190 --> 00:16:23.340
come back here and walk you
through some further analysis

00:16:23.340 --> 00:16:25.440
we've done to try to
understand what's driving

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:27.060
that very local variation.

00:16:27.060 --> 00:16:29.550
And ultimately, what we might
be able to do from a policy

00:16:29.550 --> 00:16:32.550
perspective to change
outcomes in the red colored

00:16:32.550 --> 00:16:33.940
parts of the map.

00:16:33.940 --> 00:16:36.660
So the variation that I
was showing you in Oakland

00:16:36.660 --> 00:16:39.034
occurs not just there,
but in many other cities.

00:16:39.034 --> 00:16:40.950
And I'm going to focus
on a different example,

00:16:40.950 --> 00:16:44.284
here in Seattle, where
we're doing a bunch of work.

00:16:44.284 --> 00:16:46.200
Where this is showing
you the same kind of map

00:16:46.200 --> 00:16:48.090
of upward mobility
in Seattle, you

00:16:48.090 --> 00:16:51.390
see a similar pattern of a
very broad spectrum of colors,

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:55.140
going from red and the center of
the city to much greener colors

00:16:55.140 --> 00:16:58.350
in places like Normandy
Park, south of the city.

00:16:58.350 --> 00:16:59.600
All right?

00:16:59.600 --> 00:17:04.230
So what is driving this
variation across places?

00:17:04.230 --> 00:17:07.950
Why does upward mobility
differ so much across areas?

00:17:07.950 --> 00:17:10.240
So I'm going to show you a
couple of results on that.

00:17:10.240 --> 00:17:11.849
The first point
I want to make is

00:17:11.849 --> 00:17:13.950
that most of the variation
in upward mobility

00:17:13.950 --> 00:17:15.780
that we're seeing
across these areas

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:19.450
is caused by differences
in childhood environment.

00:17:19.450 --> 00:17:21.460
So there are really
two key words there.

00:17:21.460 --> 00:17:22.815
The first is the word caused.

00:17:22.815 --> 00:17:24.690
As many of you might
know, in social science,

00:17:24.690 --> 00:17:26.220
traditionally it's
very difficult

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:28.980
to distinguish correlation
from causation.

00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:32.040
But my view is, with
the availability

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:34.260
of these large data
sets, as I'll show you,

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:36.922
we can make great strides
in distinguishing causation

00:17:36.922 --> 00:17:37.630
from correlation.

00:17:37.630 --> 00:17:39.301
And I'll illustrate
that in a second.

00:17:39.301 --> 00:17:40.800
We think we're
actually able to show

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:42.675
that this is about the
causal effect of where

00:17:42.675 --> 00:17:43.780
you're growing up.

00:17:43.780 --> 00:17:45.820
Second, it's about
childhood environment,

00:17:45.820 --> 00:17:50.390
and not about labor markets
or conditions in adulthood.

00:17:50.390 --> 00:17:52.510
So the way we establish
those findings

00:17:52.510 --> 00:17:55.690
is by studying seven
million families that

00:17:55.690 --> 00:18:00.010
move across areas, and these
data that we're working with.

00:18:00.010 --> 00:18:02.140
Rather than getting into
the statistical details

00:18:02.140 --> 00:18:04.690
of that study, I'm going
to summarize what we find

00:18:04.690 --> 00:18:06.830
with a very simple example.

00:18:06.830 --> 00:18:10.010
Let's imagine a set of families
that move from the Central

00:18:10.010 --> 00:18:12.640
District, which, as
we saw in the map

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:15.070
that I just showed you of
Seattle, kids who grew up there

00:18:15.070 --> 00:18:16.870
from birth, they
have average earnings

00:18:16.870 --> 00:18:19.387
and adulthood of $26,000 a year.

00:18:19.387 --> 00:18:21.970
And take a set of families that
move from the Central District

00:18:21.970 --> 00:18:25.240
to Normandy Park, which was in
a much bluer color on the map--

00:18:25.240 --> 00:18:27.010
higher rates of upward
mobility for kids

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:28.730
who grew up there from birth.

00:18:28.730 --> 00:18:30.640
So imagine now, set
of families that move

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:34.180
between these two places,
with kids of different ages,

00:18:34.180 --> 00:18:37.420
starting with families who move
when their child is exactly

00:18:37.420 --> 00:18:38.797
two years old.

00:18:38.797 --> 00:18:41.380
So what we do is take those kids
who move when they're exactly

00:18:41.380 --> 00:18:45.430
two, track them forward 30
years using the tax data,

00:18:45.430 --> 00:18:48.620
look at how much they're
earning in adulthood.

00:18:48.620 --> 00:18:50.440
And we see that, on
average, these kids who

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:54.910
move at exactly age two are
earning $39,000 when they're

00:18:54.910 --> 00:18:56.170
adults, in their mid 30s.

00:18:56.170 --> 00:18:57.340
All right?

00:18:57.340 --> 00:19:00.010
So that's for the kids who
move when they're exactly two.

00:19:00.010 --> 00:19:03.190
Now let's repeat that analysis
for kids who move when they're

00:19:03.190 --> 00:19:05.390
three, four, five, and so on.

00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:07.090
They make the exact same move.

00:19:07.090 --> 00:19:10.240
What you can see is a very
clear declining pattern.

00:19:10.240 --> 00:19:13.370
The later you make that move
from the Central District

00:19:13.370 --> 00:19:16.180
to Normandy Park, the
less of a gain you get.

00:19:16.180 --> 00:19:19.000
And if you move after
you're in your early 20s,

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:20.770
the relationship
is completely flat,

00:19:20.770 --> 00:19:22.282
and there's no impact at all.

00:19:22.282 --> 00:19:23.740
So what do you see
from this chart?

00:19:23.740 --> 00:19:27.050
I think there are really
three key takeaways.

00:19:27.050 --> 00:19:29.890
The first is that, apparently,
where you grow up really

00:19:29.890 --> 00:19:30.760
matters.

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:33.710
Places have a causal effect
on kids' long term outcomes.

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:35.389
It's not just that
different people

00:19:35.389 --> 00:19:36.430
live in different places.

00:19:36.430 --> 00:19:38.440
Apparently, if you
move a given child

00:19:38.440 --> 00:19:39.910
to a place that's
a few miles away,

00:19:39.910 --> 00:19:43.060
you can see very different
life outcomes for that child.

00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:45.340
That, I think, is a
very encouraging result

00:19:45.340 --> 00:19:47.771
for trying to tackle
problems like poverty

00:19:47.771 --> 00:19:49.270
and inequality,
which we've all been

00:19:49.270 --> 00:19:50.830
concerned about for decades.

00:19:50.830 --> 00:19:53.230
Because it shows that the
answer doesn't necessarily

00:19:53.230 --> 00:19:56.470
lie in switching to a completely
different economic structure--

00:19:56.470 --> 00:19:59.320
like Scandinavian countries,
or something like that.

00:19:59.320 --> 00:20:01.210
Often the answer
can be five miles

00:20:01.210 --> 00:20:05.050
down the street, where you see
completely different prospects.

00:20:05.050 --> 00:20:07.420
Second, you see that what
really seems to matter here

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:10.701
is childhood environment, rather
than conditions in adulthood.

00:20:10.701 --> 00:20:12.700
So things like jobs and
labor markets, you know,

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:14.290
obviously they matter.

00:20:14.290 --> 00:20:17.320
But where you're growing
up, childhood conditions

00:20:17.320 --> 00:20:18.700
seemed really central.

00:20:18.700 --> 00:20:20.980
And third, you see
that every extra year

00:20:20.980 --> 00:20:23.410
of exposure to a better
childhood environment

00:20:23.410 --> 00:20:24.830
improves kids' outcomes.

00:20:24.830 --> 00:20:26.860
It's not just the
very earliest years

00:20:26.860 --> 00:20:29.590
that matter, which is often
emphasized, especially

00:20:29.590 --> 00:20:31.450
recently, in policy circles.

00:20:31.450 --> 00:20:33.910
But also, if you move to a
better place when you're 10,

00:20:33.910 --> 00:20:36.284
instead of you're 20, there's
still a substantial gainful

00:20:36.284 --> 00:20:36.880
to be had.

00:20:36.880 --> 00:20:39.280
So environment matters
throughout childhood, not just

00:20:39.280 --> 00:20:41.150
in the very earliest years.

00:20:41.150 --> 00:20:44.530
So how can you use
these types of data

00:20:44.530 --> 00:20:47.684
to actually create policy change
to increase upward mobility?

00:20:47.684 --> 00:20:49.600
So given what I've just
been showing you here,

00:20:49.600 --> 00:20:51.266
one thought that might
come to your mind

00:20:51.266 --> 00:20:53.470
is, what if we help low
income families move

00:20:53.470 --> 00:20:55.506
to better neighborhoods
that we see

00:20:55.506 --> 00:20:57.880
will potentially generate
better outcomes for their kids?

00:20:57.880 --> 00:20:59.950
Now that's not going to
be a scalable solution.

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:02.120
You can't move everyone.

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:04.750
But it is actually something
practical to think about

00:21:04.750 --> 00:21:07.130
on a small scale.

00:21:07.130 --> 00:21:09.340
So just to illustrate
how we're translating

00:21:09.340 --> 00:21:13.092
some of this research to
policy change, this map--

00:21:13.092 --> 00:21:14.800
we're now showing the
same map, but we're

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:18.520
overlaying where families
that receive housing vouchers

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:21.140
in Seattle most commonly live.

00:21:21.140 --> 00:21:23.650
So we spend about
$45 billion a year

00:21:23.650 --> 00:21:26.920
in the US on various
affordable housing programs.

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:28.972
And what we see
here is that most

00:21:28.972 --> 00:21:31.180
of those vouchers that people
get from the government

00:21:31.180 --> 00:21:34.510
are used to rent housing in
pretty low opportunity areas.

00:21:34.510 --> 00:21:37.310
They're clustered in the red
colored parts of the map.

00:21:37.310 --> 00:21:40.307
So in light of this evidence,
we've been working with

00:21:40.307 --> 00:21:42.640
the Seattle Housing Authority,
and the Housing and Urban

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:45.820
Development Agency in the US,
to develop a pilot program which

00:21:45.820 --> 00:21:49.900
we're testing using a RCT-- a
randomized controlled trial--

00:21:49.900 --> 00:21:52.180
where we're helping families
with housing vouchers

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:54.880
move to high opportunity
areas by providing them

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:57.255
information, by
recruiting landlords

00:21:57.255 --> 00:21:58.630
to make them more
willing to rent

00:21:58.630 --> 00:22:00.490
their apartments
to these tenants,

00:22:00.490 --> 00:22:02.950
and providing
housing broker search

00:22:02.950 --> 00:22:06.610
services to help you find units
in these higher opportunity

00:22:06.610 --> 00:22:07.990
areas.

00:22:07.990 --> 00:22:10.990
And while I don't have
results to show yet,

00:22:10.990 --> 00:22:13.950
preliminary signs are this
is working incredibly well.

00:22:13.950 --> 00:22:17.020
At essentially no incremental
cost to taxpayers,

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:19.870
you can help families access
much higher opportunity

00:22:19.870 --> 00:22:22.130
areas where their kids
will do much better.

00:22:22.130 --> 00:22:23.950
So this is a
concrete illustration

00:22:23.950 --> 00:22:26.470
of how you can take this
type of research and data

00:22:26.470 --> 00:22:29.004
and translate it to
change on the ground.

00:22:29.004 --> 00:22:30.670
Now I want to take a
couple more minutes

00:22:30.670 --> 00:22:33.760
to discuss a
different direction.

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:36.640
So this is, I think,
a solution that's

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:37.910
relevant for some families.

00:22:37.910 --> 00:22:40.085
But as I was saying
earlier, it's not scalable.

00:22:40.085 --> 00:22:42.460
You can do this, maybe, for
a couple of million families,

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:44.110
but you can't move everyone.

00:22:44.110 --> 00:22:48.670
So the deeper question is, how
can you improve upward mobility

00:22:48.670 --> 00:22:50.080
in the places that
currently have

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:51.330
low levels of upward mobility?

00:22:51.330 --> 00:22:53.410
And so that's what
our research agenda

00:22:53.410 --> 00:22:57.220
is centrally focused on now,
and in the coming years.

00:22:57.220 --> 00:23:00.070
As a first step, one useful
way to think about it

00:23:00.070 --> 00:23:03.220
is, what are the
characteristics of areas where

00:23:03.220 --> 00:23:04.767
we see high levels of mobility?

00:23:04.767 --> 00:23:06.850
Are there certain common
features of those places?

00:23:06.850 --> 00:23:08.200
And the answer is yes.

00:23:08.200 --> 00:23:11.150
They tend to have four
systematic characteristics.

00:23:11.150 --> 00:23:14.740
They tend to have lower poverty
rates, more stable family

00:23:14.740 --> 00:23:18.640
structures-- so a larger
share of two parent families.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:22.190
They tend to have higher
levels of social capital--

00:23:22.190 --> 00:23:24.520
so think of the old adage
that it takes a village

00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:25.780
to raise a child.

00:23:25.780 --> 00:23:27.520
Places with a lot
of social capital,

00:23:27.520 --> 00:23:30.190
for instance, Salt Lake
City with the Mormon church,

00:23:30.190 --> 00:23:33.117
those types of places tend to
have high levels of mobility.

00:23:33.117 --> 00:23:35.200
And then finally, as you
might expect intuitively,

00:23:35.200 --> 00:23:36.640
places with better schools--

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:39.100
both at the K through 12 level,
and access to high quality

00:23:39.100 --> 00:23:41.170
higher education-- tend
to have higher levels

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:41.990
of upward mobility.

00:23:41.990 --> 00:23:46.720
So this gives you some sense
of the types of areas I

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:48.580
think we should be focusing on.

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:50.740
It doesn't necessarily
tell you, though,

00:23:50.740 --> 00:23:53.710
what exact interventions you
should implement in order

00:23:53.710 --> 00:23:56.120
to increase economic
opportunity.

00:23:56.120 --> 00:23:59.590
And so the direction that we're
headed in is partnering with

00:23:59.590 --> 00:24:02.680
many cities across
America-- in this case,

00:24:02.680 --> 00:24:04.610
I'm giving you an
example from Charlotte--

00:24:04.610 --> 00:24:06.970
where we're using this
Opportunity Atlas data

00:24:06.970 --> 00:24:09.490
to ask what types
of programs, what's

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:11.570
going on in neighborhoods
in your city

00:24:11.570 --> 00:24:13.330
where we're seeing
much better outcomes?

00:24:13.330 --> 00:24:15.460
Can we then learn something
about interventions

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:18.369
that might work, by
testing new things,

00:24:18.369 --> 00:24:20.410
or looking at historical
data about interventions

00:24:20.410 --> 00:24:23.530
that have been attempted and
looking at the outcomes that

00:24:23.530 --> 00:24:24.660
have emerged?

00:24:24.660 --> 00:24:28.330
OK, so let me wrap
up, since I want

00:24:28.330 --> 00:24:30.690
to make sure we have time
to get to your questions,

00:24:30.690 --> 00:24:34.790
by just making one
final point here.

00:24:34.790 --> 00:24:37.120
Which is, usually we
think about issues

00:24:37.120 --> 00:24:40.060
of equality of opportunity from
the perspective of principles

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:40.660
of justice.

00:24:40.660 --> 00:24:43.570
Everyone should have a
shot at the American dream,

00:24:43.570 --> 00:24:45.730
no matter what
their background is.

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:47.920
But improving opportunities
for upward mobility,

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:49.545
I think it's important
to keep in mind,

00:24:49.545 --> 00:24:53.060
can also be important simply
for increasing economic growth.

00:24:53.060 --> 00:24:54.780
And so to illustrate
that, I want

00:24:54.780 --> 00:24:57.220
to show you one
final piece of data

00:24:57.220 --> 00:25:00.147
which focuses on a specific
pathway to upward mobility

00:25:00.147 --> 00:25:02.230
that's very relevant here
in Silicon Valley, which

00:25:02.230 --> 00:25:03.245
is innovation.

00:25:03.245 --> 00:25:04.870
And so to do that,
we're going to study

00:25:04.870 --> 00:25:08.230
the lives of 750,000
patent holders in the US

00:25:08.230 --> 00:25:11.680
by linking the universe of
patent records to the tax data

00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:15.370
that we used in the previous
studies that I described.

00:25:15.370 --> 00:25:18.610
So I'll start out with this
chart here, which shows you,

00:25:18.610 --> 00:25:21.190
in some sense, your probability
of becoming an inventor,

00:25:21.190 --> 00:25:22.530
using patents as a proxy.

00:25:22.530 --> 00:25:25.000
I recognize that has
some limitations.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:28.210
But plotting your probability
of having a patent in your mid

00:25:28.210 --> 00:25:30.880
30s-- by the time
you're 35, or so--

00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:32.930
versus your parents' income.

00:25:32.930 --> 00:25:34.480
And you can see
that if you happen

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:37.960
to be born to parents in the top
1% of the income distribution,

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:40.986
you're about 10 times as likely
to go on to become an inventor

00:25:40.986 --> 00:25:43.360
as if you happened to be born
to parents below the median

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:44.980
of the income distribution.

00:25:44.980 --> 00:25:49.150
Now, one potential explanation
for why you see this big gap

00:25:49.150 --> 00:25:51.200
is that this is about
differences in environment,

00:25:51.200 --> 00:25:53.200
and resources, and schools--
the types of things

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:54.820
I've been talking about here.

00:25:54.820 --> 00:25:56.560
A different explanation
is that this is

00:25:56.560 --> 00:25:58.000
about differences in ability.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.569
Perhaps the kids born to parents
at the top 1% of the income

00:26:00.569 --> 00:26:02.110
distribution-- you
know, your parents

00:26:02.110 --> 00:26:04.362
had to be pretty talented
in order to get there.

00:26:04.362 --> 00:26:06.820
There's genetic transmission
of ability across generations,

00:26:06.820 --> 00:26:09.580
maybe that's why you're more
likely to become an inventor.

00:26:09.580 --> 00:26:12.160
One way to distinguish
between those two explanations

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:16.600
is to use data on test scores
early in childhood as a way

00:26:16.600 --> 00:26:20.980
to get a rough sense of whether
aptitude seems to matter here.

00:26:20.980 --> 00:26:22.450
And so this chart--

00:26:22.450 --> 00:26:25.630
same y-axis, we're
plotting pattern rates--

00:26:25.630 --> 00:26:29.290
but now versus your third
grade and math test scores,

00:26:29.290 --> 00:26:31.910
as opposed to your
parents' income.

00:26:31.910 --> 00:26:33.550
And so you can see
here that if you

00:26:33.550 --> 00:26:36.670
happen to be at the top of
your third grade math class

00:26:36.670 --> 00:26:39.850
you're much more likely to go on
to have a patent than if you're

00:26:39.850 --> 00:26:42.380
below something like
the 90th percentile.

00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:45.040
Now, more interesting for
what I'm talking about here

00:26:45.040 --> 00:26:48.190
is, if you then split
that out, looking

00:26:48.190 --> 00:26:51.310
at kids from high income
families in the green--

00:26:51.310 --> 00:26:53.200
families in the top 20%--

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:55.810
versus low and middle
income families in the gray,

00:26:55.810 --> 00:26:57.940
you see a striking pattern.

00:26:57.940 --> 00:27:00.460
Which is that high scoring
children are much more

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:02.740
likely to become
inventors if they're

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:03.880
from high income families.

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:05.140
If you're from a
low income family

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:07.348
and you're at the top of
your third grade math class,

00:27:07.348 --> 00:27:09.010
it doesn't do a
whole lot in terms

00:27:09.010 --> 00:27:11.590
of your odds of
becoming an inventor.

00:27:11.590 --> 00:27:14.230
So to put it differently,
apparently, in America,

00:27:14.230 --> 00:27:16.970
in order to become an inventor
you seem to need two things.

00:27:16.970 --> 00:27:19.180
You need have high
quantitative aptitude,

00:27:19.180 --> 00:27:21.400
as measured by your
third grade math test,

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:23.410
and you need to be from
a high income family.

00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:26.200
And so you can see why,
from that perspective,

00:27:26.200 --> 00:27:27.880
increasing equality
of opportunity

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:30.460
could potentially be of
benefit to all of us.

00:27:30.460 --> 00:27:32.890
Bringing these talented
kids through the pipeline

00:27:32.890 --> 00:27:35.470
wouldn't just benefit
them but would potentially

00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:38.120
benefit all of us by increasing
the amount of innovation.

00:27:38.120 --> 00:27:40.510
And so let me end
by just quantifying

00:27:40.510 --> 00:27:42.480
the magnitude of that.

00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:45.090
If women, minorities, and
children from low income kids

00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:48.162
were to invent as the same
rate as high income white men,

00:27:48.162 --> 00:27:49.620
the data that I've
been showing you

00:27:49.620 --> 00:27:52.560
imply that the patent rate, or
the innovation rate, in America

00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:53.310
would quadruple.

00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:55.860
So there's a tremendous amount
of talent, in some sense,

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:57.670
being left on the table.

00:27:57.670 --> 00:27:59.550
And I think figuring
out a way to harness

00:27:59.550 --> 00:28:02.640
that talent would be of
great benefit to those kids,

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:05.640
and more broadly help us
restore the American dream.

00:28:05.640 --> 00:28:06.782
So let me stop there.

00:28:06.782 --> 00:28:07.490
Thanks very much.

