00:33:53.150 --> 00:33:56.510
is that the way in which
economic growth is now

00:33:56.510 --> 00:33:59.240
distributed is extremely
different from the way

00:33:59.240 --> 00:34:01.610
economic growth was
distributed in the past.

00:34:01.610 --> 00:34:04.520
So growth rates, as you know,
are a little bit lower today

00:34:04.520 --> 00:34:06.920
than they were in
the 1950s and 1960s.

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:12.227
But we show in that paper that
if you had the same growth

00:34:12.227 --> 00:34:14.810
rates that you had in the past--
high growth rates like we had

00:34:14.810 --> 00:34:16.280
in the '50s and '60s--

00:34:16.280 --> 00:34:20.810
but divided that growth in the
way that it's shared today,

00:34:20.810 --> 00:34:24.469
across the income distribution,
you would stem only one third

00:34:24.469 --> 00:34:27.069
of the decline in the
fraction of kids doing better

00:34:27.069 --> 00:34:27.860
than their parents.

00:34:27.860 --> 00:34:30.949
Most of the decline
is due to the fact

00:34:30.949 --> 00:34:33.320
that median wages,
however you measure it,

00:34:33.320 --> 00:34:37.984
have largely stagnated
relative to growth at the top.

00:34:37.984 --> 00:34:39.650
HAL VARIAN: So there's
this other side--

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:42.290
your colleague Chad Jones has
written a very interesting

00:34:42.290 --> 00:34:46.429
paper about why we saw such
increases in productivity

00:34:46.429 --> 00:34:48.880
during the '60s and '70s.

00:34:48.880 --> 00:34:52.670
And this was-- potentially,
he doesn't establish this,

00:34:52.670 --> 00:34:55.790
but by simulation-- it's
potentially the fact

00:34:55.790 --> 00:34:58.030
that lots of barriers
broke down for women

00:34:58.030 --> 00:35:00.140
and for African-Americans,
and they

00:35:00.140 --> 00:35:03.260
were able to enter the labor
force, dramatically increasing

00:35:03.260 --> 00:35:04.640
productivity.

00:35:04.640 --> 00:35:07.610
But at the same time, they
were pulled away from the jobs

00:35:07.610 --> 00:35:10.920
as teachers, and librarians, and
other low income service jobs.

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:13.730
So what was an opportunity
for one group of people,

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:15.930
turned out to be a
problem in terms out

00:35:15.930 --> 00:35:17.220
as the community they served.

00:35:17.220 --> 00:35:21.860
So you have to balance these two
interests to really understand

00:35:21.860 --> 00:35:25.122
what kinds of behaviors
should be improved.

00:35:25.122 --> 00:35:27.330
RAJ CHETTY: And I think
that's very interesting, Hal.

00:35:27.330 --> 00:35:29.080
I mean, there might
even be dynamic effects.

00:35:29.080 --> 00:35:29.580
Right?

00:35:29.580 --> 00:35:31.910
So if you imagine--

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:35.120
people have argued that
in the past the quality

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:36.770
of the teaching
workforce was greater,

00:35:36.770 --> 00:35:38.990
because you had many
high-skilled women who would

00:35:38.990 --> 00:35:41.780
choose to go into teaching,
whereas now they don't.

00:35:41.780 --> 00:35:44.870
And that, as you noted, could
have potentially contributed

00:35:44.870 --> 00:35:47.120
to greater productivity
in the '50s and '60s.

00:35:47.120 --> 00:35:49.690
But when you now think about
the current generation,

00:35:49.690 --> 00:35:51.990
and you think about the
long-term impacts of teachers,

00:35:51.990 --> 00:35:55.014
it may actually have adverse
effects on productivity now.

00:35:55.014 --> 00:35:55.680
HAL VARIAN: Yes.

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:57.480
RAJ CHETTY: Yeah.

00:35:57.480 --> 00:35:59.330
HAL VARIAN: One of the
interesting findings

00:35:59.330 --> 00:36:06.680
that you said, when high income
people move into an area, that

00:36:06.680 --> 00:36:08.900
displaces, or
potentially displaces,

00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:10.845
people who are already there.

00:36:10.845 --> 00:36:13.220
On the other hand, there been
other studies from, Moretti

00:36:13.220 --> 00:36:16.370
and so on, that show that
when you see high tech,

00:36:16.370 --> 00:36:18.640
high paying firms
move into an area,

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:22.860
five new jobs are created
over the course of a decade.

00:36:22.860 --> 00:36:25.257
So there's a lot of--

00:36:25.257 --> 00:36:27.590
I suppose I shouldn't call
it trickle down-- but trickle

00:36:27.590 --> 00:36:31.560
across where you bring
economic resources in an area,

00:36:31.560 --> 00:36:35.212
it tends to impact most
of the participants.

00:36:35.212 --> 00:36:37.170
RAJ CHETTY: So I think
that's absolutely right.

00:36:37.170 --> 00:36:40.130
This is something we're studying
in more detail at the moment.

00:36:40.130 --> 00:36:43.830
Basically, what are the effects
of a new company coming in--

00:36:43.830 --> 00:36:46.280
Amazon, of course,
the new headquarters,

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:48.080
things like that--

00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:51.290
what impact would that
have on the people

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:52.610
who were already there?

00:36:52.610 --> 00:36:54.667
So the fundamental
advance we're able to make

00:36:54.667 --> 00:36:56.750
with the types of data
I've been showing you today

00:36:56.750 --> 00:36:59.190
is that we're able to look
at things longitudinally.

00:36:59.190 --> 00:37:01.820
You're able to track a
given person over time.

00:37:01.820 --> 00:37:02.870
Why is that important?

00:37:02.870 --> 00:37:05.060
You might see that
when a company moves

00:37:05.060 --> 00:37:08.780
in, lots of new jobs
are created, et cetera,

00:37:08.780 --> 00:37:10.850
the place starts to look
much richer, in terms

00:37:10.850 --> 00:37:12.050
of the average incomes
of the people who

00:37:12.050 --> 00:37:13.220
are there, and so forth.

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:15.470
A lot of that could be
driven by migration, right?

00:37:15.470 --> 00:37:17.600
Lots of new people
come in, lower income

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:20.100
people get displaced, the
place looks much better.

00:37:20.100 --> 00:37:22.140
But have you actually improved
the outcomes of the people who

00:37:22.140 --> 00:37:22.973
were actually there?

00:37:22.973 --> 00:37:25.730
We actually, I think, do not
really know the answer to that.

00:37:25.730 --> 00:37:27.590
What I've been showing
you here is that,

00:37:27.590 --> 00:37:31.107
at least for the kids
growing up in those places,

00:37:31.107 --> 00:37:32.690
it's not a one to
one thing, that they

00:37:32.690 --> 00:37:34.100
capture those benefits.

00:37:34.100 --> 00:37:36.764
And that's because there's
so much mobility in the US.

00:37:36.764 --> 00:37:38.180
You know, of course
lots of people

00:37:38.180 --> 00:37:40.310
are going to move
to Silicon Valley

00:37:40.310 --> 00:37:42.160
to get the great
jobs that are here.

00:37:42.160 --> 00:37:45.480
It doesn't necessarily mean that
the kids growing up in San Jose

00:37:45.480 --> 00:37:46.730
are going to directly benefit.

00:37:46.730 --> 00:37:48.521
And I think we have to
think hard about how

00:37:48.521 --> 00:37:50.150
you make that connection.

00:37:50.150 --> 00:37:52.490
I think companies like
Google can potentially

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:54.990
play a role in that, thinking
beyond attracting the best

00:37:54.990 --> 00:37:55.490
talent.

00:37:55.490 --> 00:37:57.950
How do you cultivate
the talent in the areas

00:37:57.950 --> 00:37:59.180
where the company is?

00:37:59.180 --> 00:38:02.360
HAL VARIAN: Yeah, and I
think this mobility, which

00:38:02.360 --> 00:38:04.760
you referred to,
geographic mobility

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:06.604
has really slowed
down significantly

00:38:06.604 --> 00:38:07.520
in the last few years.

00:38:07.520 --> 00:38:10.640
It's much harder, much
more expensive, much rarer

00:38:10.640 --> 00:38:13.690
to see lower income people
moving into high income areas,

00:38:13.690 --> 00:38:15.530
because, of course,
they can't afford them.

00:38:15.530 --> 00:38:16.613
RAJ CHETTY: Too expensive.

00:38:16.613 --> 00:38:17.410
HAL VARIAN: Yeah.

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:21.670
On this social responsibility,
when Google was, of course,

00:38:21.670 --> 00:38:25.330
opening a lot of offices
in areas around the US,

00:38:25.330 --> 00:38:26.320
what do you think--

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:28.330
what would you
recommend or suggest

00:38:28.330 --> 00:38:33.220
that we could do to
help be a positive force

00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:35.170
in the local communities
in those areas?

00:38:35.170 --> 00:38:38.230
RAJ CHETTY: I mean, I
think one thing we find--

00:38:38.230 --> 00:38:40.660
so let's go back to the
inventors data for a minute.

00:38:40.660 --> 00:38:42.340
So one of the
interesting patterns,

00:38:42.340 --> 00:38:44.560
which I didn't
discuss, is if you

00:38:44.560 --> 00:38:48.370
ask, what is driving these sharp
differences in innovation rates

00:38:48.370 --> 00:38:51.340
across low and high income
families, a lot of it

00:38:51.340 --> 00:38:53.230
seems to be about exposure.

00:38:53.230 --> 00:38:55.490
So let me give you
the following example.

00:38:55.490 --> 00:38:58.120
If we take two kids who
currently live in Boston,

00:38:58.120 --> 00:38:59.920
and let's say they're at MIT.

00:38:59.920 --> 00:39:02.530
And one of those kids
grew up in Silicon Valley,

00:39:02.530 --> 00:39:04.250
and one of those kids
grew up, let's say,

00:39:04.250 --> 00:39:06.670
in Minneapolis, which has
a lot of medical device

00:39:06.670 --> 00:39:08.020
manufacturers.

00:39:08.020 --> 00:39:10.450
We see that the kid who
grew up in Minneapolis

00:39:10.450 --> 00:39:12.070
is much more likely
to go on to have

00:39:12.070 --> 00:39:14.112
a patent in medical devices.

00:39:14.112 --> 00:39:15.820
And the kid who grew
up in Silicon Valley

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:18.550
is much more likely to go
on to patent in computers.

00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:22.540
More generally, the chances
that you become an inventor,

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:24.070
and the field in
which you innovate,

00:39:24.070 --> 00:39:27.340
are greatly influenced by the
area in which you grow up,

00:39:27.340 --> 00:39:29.290
and the the environment
in which you grew up.

00:39:29.290 --> 00:39:31.340
And that operates in
very specific ways.

00:39:31.340 --> 00:39:33.310
So when women grow
up in areas where

00:39:33.310 --> 00:39:36.520
there are a lot of female
inventors in a given field,

00:39:36.520 --> 00:39:39.250
they're much more likely to go
on to innovate in that field.

00:39:39.250 --> 00:39:41.480
But if there are more male
inventors in that field,

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:44.620
it has no impact at all on
women's innovation rates.

00:39:44.620 --> 00:39:46.330
And so all of that,
to me, suggests

00:39:46.330 --> 00:39:48.950
that what matters is exposure.

00:39:48.950 --> 00:39:51.130
And so if you think about
a company like Google

00:39:51.130 --> 00:39:53.590
going into a new area,
of course there's

00:39:53.590 --> 00:39:55.510
going to be a lot of
attraction of top talent

00:39:55.510 --> 00:39:56.884
from other places.

00:39:56.884 --> 00:39:58.300
But thinking about
how you develop

00:39:58.300 --> 00:40:01.480
programs so that you
connect with the kids

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:03.439
in local schools--

00:40:03.439 --> 00:40:05.230
you know, you might
have mentoring programs

00:40:05.230 --> 00:40:08.140
or other things that provide
that sort of exposure

00:40:08.140 --> 00:40:09.130
in a scalable way--

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:12.430
I actually think, designed
properly and tested carefully

00:40:12.430 --> 00:40:14.080
with these types
of data, could have

00:40:14.080 --> 00:40:16.270
quite a substantial impact.

00:40:16.270 --> 00:40:18.500
HAL VARIAN: And we have done
some programs like that.

00:40:18.500 --> 00:40:20.980
I was talking,
actually, at my bank,

00:40:20.980 --> 00:40:22.780
and the teller said,
oh my gosh, my kid's

00:40:22.780 --> 00:40:25.210
taking your computer
course from Google.

00:40:25.210 --> 00:40:29.140
I never even knew there was
one, but we've been doing it

00:40:29.140 --> 00:40:30.024
for several years.

00:40:30.024 --> 00:40:31.690
RAJ CHETTY: Maybe
evaluating the impacts

00:40:31.690 --> 00:40:33.190
of those things, figuring
out how to scale them,

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:34.315
would be quite interesting.

00:40:34.315 --> 00:40:36.500
HAL VARIAN: Yeah, that can
have a really big impact,

00:40:36.500 --> 00:40:38.650
I think, from Saturday
morning programs,

00:40:38.650 --> 00:40:40.770
after school
programs, and so on.

00:40:40.770 --> 00:40:42.520
One thing that we've
been looking at a lot

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:45.890
lately is future work issues.

00:40:45.890 --> 00:40:49.060
And as you know, there's a
lot of issues about changing

00:40:49.060 --> 00:40:51.100
demographics, and
composition of work,

00:40:51.100 --> 00:40:54.370
what kind of job opportunities
are going to be available.

00:40:54.370 --> 00:40:57.040
Has any of your work shed
light on some of those issues?

00:40:57.040 --> 00:41:01.095
Or is that something
that's for the future?

00:41:01.095 --> 00:41:02.470
RAJ CHETTY: Let
me say two things

00:41:02.470 --> 00:41:04.470
on that-- one that relates
to our work, and just

00:41:04.470 --> 00:41:05.680
a broader reaction.

00:41:05.680 --> 00:41:08.290
So one of the things
we find in our work

00:41:08.290 --> 00:41:11.840
is, what seems to predict
longer term success,

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:13.690
especially in the
current economy,

00:41:13.690 --> 00:41:16.130
is not just technical skills.

00:41:16.130 --> 00:41:19.150
I gave you an example with
math test scores, for instance.

00:41:19.150 --> 00:41:22.060
But more broadly, if you look
at so-called non cognitive

00:41:22.060 --> 00:41:22.670
skills--

00:41:22.670 --> 00:41:24.820
so, measures of social
skills, how well do you

00:41:24.820 --> 00:41:27.640
get along with others,
discipline, and so forth--

00:41:27.640 --> 00:41:29.440
those are actually
more predictive

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:31.810
in the general
population of longer term

00:41:31.810 --> 00:41:34.487
success than technical skills.

00:41:34.487 --> 00:41:36.820
And I think that's going to
be especially relevant going

00:41:36.820 --> 00:41:39.280
forward, as man
is, in some sense

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:42.760
competing with the machine,
it's in the more social kind

00:41:42.760 --> 00:41:45.580
of nebulous dimension--

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:47.920
interacting with
people, and so forth--

00:41:47.920 --> 00:41:51.460
where I think there are
big returns to be had.

00:41:51.460 --> 00:41:53.320
And so figuring
out how you provide

00:41:53.320 --> 00:41:57.040
those skills, in addition to
technical skills-- or some work

00:41:57.040 --> 00:41:59.920
showing that it's really the
combination of those two things

00:41:59.920 --> 00:42:01.850
that's critical for
success in the long run.

00:42:01.850 --> 00:42:03.820
So I think thinking
about how we--

00:42:03.820 --> 00:42:06.730
education is not typically
structured with that in mind.

00:42:06.730 --> 00:42:08.230
Traditional systems
of education are

00:42:08.230 --> 00:42:10.396
about teaching a certain
set of technical knowledge.

00:42:10.396 --> 00:42:12.070
I think figuring
out how we adapt

00:42:12.070 --> 00:42:14.390
to that is very important.

00:42:14.390 --> 00:42:16.540
My broader reaction
is, people, I think,

00:42:16.540 --> 00:42:18.610
are rightly concerned
about the future of work.

00:42:18.610 --> 00:42:22.150
But I would note that
100 years ago, people

00:42:22.150 --> 00:42:24.770
were also extremely concerned
about the future of work,

00:42:24.770 --> 00:42:26.560
and thought that
once we had cars

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:29.710
and all these other machines
there'd be nothing to do.

00:42:29.710 --> 00:42:31.780
And I think humans
are inventive people,

00:42:31.780 --> 00:42:33.700
and we will figure
out other things

00:42:33.700 --> 00:42:36.085
to do as the economy evolves.

00:42:36.085 --> 00:42:39.280
HAL VARIAN: Yeah, another
important point is that

00:42:39.280 --> 00:42:43.420
the economic dynacism we saw
in the '60s and '70s from

00:42:43.420 --> 00:42:46.750
the entry of men and women
into the labor force--

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:51.100
baby boomers and women who
were busy being able to take up

00:42:51.100 --> 00:42:55.390
opportunities outside
the traditional jobs--

00:42:55.390 --> 00:42:56.870
that's all running
in reverse now.

00:42:56.870 --> 00:42:59.140
The baby boomers are
retiring, and women's

00:42:59.140 --> 00:43:01.990
participation the labor force
has leveled out, or even

00:43:01.990 --> 00:43:03.740
gone down a little bit.

00:43:03.740 --> 00:43:06.600
So what we're
seeing is a society,

00:43:06.600 --> 00:43:08.200
in most developed
countries, that's

00:43:08.200 --> 00:43:10.450
really aging very rapidly.

00:43:10.450 --> 00:43:14.390
And you'd expect to see
maybe less dynamic behavior.

00:43:14.390 --> 00:43:16.805
Might see less support for
education, for example,

00:43:16.805 --> 00:43:19.250
from that political change.

00:43:19.250 --> 00:43:21.070
RAJ CHETTY: Possibly, possibly.

00:43:21.070 --> 00:43:24.080
HAL VARIAN: And there are
big changes, geographically,

00:43:24.080 --> 00:43:26.650
between what's happening,
let's say in Utah and Nevada,

00:43:26.650 --> 00:43:28.680
and what's happening in
Wisconsin and Michigan.

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:29.638
RAJ CHETTY: Absolutely.

00:43:29.638 --> 00:43:31.359
HAL VARIAN: So quite
interesting areas.

