00:44:46.730 --> 00:44:51.710
like the best places in
Seattle, or Iowa, et cetera,

00:44:51.710 --> 00:44:53.490
even within Charlotte itself.

00:44:53.490 --> 00:44:55.665
So it's not entirely
a sea of red.

00:44:55.665 --> 00:44:57.290
And I think that's
extremely important,

00:44:57.290 --> 00:44:58.956
because it shows
people in Charlotte you

00:44:58.956 --> 00:45:01.520
can look within your
community to figure out

00:45:01.520 --> 00:45:04.770
how you potentially expand
those opportunities elsewhere.

00:45:04.770 --> 00:45:06.710
HAL VARIAN: What about
the Dory question here,

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:10.850
on who becomes an
inventor in America?

00:45:10.850 --> 00:45:12.770
This company's
demographic disparity--

00:45:12.770 --> 00:45:14.240
what would you
recommend to bridge

00:45:14.240 --> 00:45:17.960
this gap between the
socioeconomic issues

00:45:17.960 --> 00:45:22.229
that impact innovation and
what we're trying to do here?

00:45:22.229 --> 00:45:24.020
RAJ CHETTY: I mean, I
think it comes back--

00:45:24.020 --> 00:45:26.270
some of it can be done at
the level of a company.

00:45:26.270 --> 00:45:28.187
I think some of it comes
back to social issues

00:45:28.187 --> 00:45:30.561
that the government and the
broader public has to tackle.

00:45:30.561 --> 00:45:31.130
Right?

00:45:31.130 --> 00:45:33.500
So what I will say--

00:45:33.500 --> 00:45:36.260
looking at this question on
disparities in demographics,

00:45:36.260 --> 00:45:39.050
one thing that comes to mind
is, if you don't do anything,

00:45:39.050 --> 00:45:41.870
these things are changing,
but at an extremely slow rate.

00:45:41.870 --> 00:45:44.840
So we see, for instance, if
you look at gender disparities

00:45:44.840 --> 00:45:49.640
in innovation, 14% of patents
in the US currently go to women,

00:45:49.640 --> 00:45:52.160
and that's changing at a rate
of a quarter of a percentage

00:45:52.160 --> 00:45:53.510
point per year.

00:45:53.510 --> 00:45:55.760
It's increasing at a rate
of a quarter of a percentage

00:45:55.760 --> 00:45:57.280
point per year, so if
you just do the math,

00:45:57.280 --> 00:45:59.180
that means it's going
to take another 140

00:45:59.180 --> 00:46:02.535
years to reach gender parity at
the current rate of progress.

00:46:02.535 --> 00:46:03.500
Right?

00:46:03.500 --> 00:46:07.751
So the question is, how
do you accelerate that?

00:46:07.751 --> 00:46:10.250
At some level I feel like it's
kind of a chicken and the egg

00:46:10.250 --> 00:46:14.810
problem, where if there were
more women in innovation

00:46:14.810 --> 00:46:16.520
in companies like
Google, I think

00:46:16.520 --> 00:46:20.250
more girls would be inspired
to pursue those careers.

00:46:20.250 --> 00:46:23.030
So the question is how you
get that cycle started.

00:46:23.030 --> 00:46:25.596
I think some of it comes back
to some of the broader factors

00:46:25.596 --> 00:46:27.470
that I was talking about
on other dimensions,

00:46:27.470 --> 00:46:29.180
thinking about
racial disparities,

00:46:29.180 --> 00:46:31.730
socioeconomic
disparities, schools,

00:46:31.730 --> 00:46:34.100
the segregation in
our neighborhoods,

00:46:34.100 --> 00:46:36.870
the lack of contact between
low and high income people,

00:46:36.870 --> 00:46:37.770
things like that.

00:46:37.770 --> 00:46:39.644
HAL VARIAN: I would be
very interested to see

00:46:39.644 --> 00:46:43.550
what happens to schools
in New York, where

00:46:43.550 --> 00:46:44.702
Amazon is moving in.

00:46:44.702 --> 00:46:45.410
RAJ CHETTY: Yeah.

00:46:45.410 --> 00:46:46.550
HAL VARIAN: There'll
be a proliferation

00:46:46.550 --> 00:46:48.145
of private schools, of course.

00:46:48.145 --> 00:46:50.840
There'll be a proliferation
of charter schools.

00:46:50.840 --> 00:46:53.060
And, of course, the
New York educational

00:46:53.060 --> 00:46:55.370
schools, which are
pretty good compared

00:46:55.370 --> 00:46:58.730
to the national average.

00:46:58.730 --> 00:46:59.900
Question here.

00:46:59.900 --> 00:47:03.422
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks so much
for coming to speak with us.

00:47:03.422 --> 00:47:04.880
One thing that I
thought was really

00:47:04.880 --> 00:47:06.680
compelling about your
talk was the focus

00:47:06.680 --> 00:47:09.470
on from big data
to hyperlocal data,

00:47:09.470 --> 00:47:12.560
and how we can begin
exploring those kinds

00:47:12.560 --> 00:47:14.420
of interesting
topics, to figure out

00:47:14.420 --> 00:47:18.620
ways to change our
economic mobility.

00:47:18.620 --> 00:47:21.311
At Google I'm talking strategy
analytics in the human capital

00:47:21.311 --> 00:47:23.060
side, so it's also
interesting from there.

00:47:23.060 --> 00:47:25.910
But outside of work I run a
nonprofit called Consult Your

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:28.060
Community, that helps
college students work

00:47:28.060 --> 00:47:30.870
with small business owners to
kind of focus on this space.

00:47:30.870 --> 00:47:33.170
So my question for
both of you is,

00:47:33.170 --> 00:47:35.960
what's the role in local
nonprofits and community

00:47:35.960 --> 00:47:38.270
builders in helping
accelerate this change

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:40.354
from a different angle?

00:47:40.354 --> 00:47:42.020
RAJ CHETTY: So I think
local nonprofits,

00:47:42.020 --> 00:47:43.390
as you can see
with these data, I

00:47:43.390 --> 00:47:44.973
think they can play
a huge role, given

00:47:44.973 --> 00:47:48.800
that the scale of the problem
appears to be fairly local.

00:47:48.800 --> 00:47:50.669
What I think would be
really useful to do,

00:47:50.669 --> 00:47:52.460
and what we're trying
to do with our group,

00:47:52.460 --> 00:47:54.168
Opportunity Insights,
with these data is,

00:47:54.168 --> 00:47:58.277
connect with lots of nonprofits
like Big Brothers Big Sisters,

00:47:58.277 --> 00:48:00.110
other groups like that
that are doing things

00:48:00.110 --> 00:48:04.970
in mentoring or racial issues,
criminal justice, et cetera,

00:48:04.970 --> 00:48:08.150
to try to evaluate more
systematically what

00:48:08.150 --> 00:48:10.290
has the most significant
impacts in the long run.

00:48:10.290 --> 00:48:10.790
Right?

00:48:10.790 --> 00:48:14.030
I feel like there is a bit
of a disconnect between lots

00:48:14.030 --> 00:48:17.390
of people who are doing really
good work on the ground, where

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:19.550
they have a sense that
this might be working,

00:48:19.550 --> 00:48:21.810
but how do we scale that?

00:48:21.810 --> 00:48:23.960
How do we think about,
in a cost effective way,

00:48:23.960 --> 00:48:27.200
which aspects of different
programs are successful?

00:48:27.200 --> 00:48:30.140
I think these sorts of data can
be useful in figuring that out.

00:48:30.140 --> 00:48:32.015
And there's a disconnect
between those people

00:48:32.015 --> 00:48:33.830
on the ground and
researchers who

00:48:33.830 --> 00:48:36.159
may not be as aware of
the various programs

00:48:36.159 --> 00:48:37.700
that people are
trying, and so forth.

00:48:37.700 --> 00:48:39.325
So one of the things
we're trying to do

00:48:39.325 --> 00:48:41.570
is bring those things
together, and hopefully

00:48:41.570 --> 00:48:45.170
have more to say about
it in the coming years.

00:48:45.170 --> 00:48:47.930
HAL VARIAN: What about this
question on the correlation

00:48:47.930 --> 00:48:50.140
causation issue?

00:48:50.140 --> 00:48:51.936
An alternative
hypothesis might be,

00:48:51.936 --> 00:48:53.810
parents who are really
interested in the kids

00:48:53.810 --> 00:48:54.884
might move earlier.

00:48:54.884 --> 00:48:55.550
RAJ CHETTY: Yup.

00:48:55.550 --> 00:48:56.780
HAL VARIAN: And by
the way, as you know,

00:48:56.780 --> 00:48:59.090
there are studies of
immigration, where immigrants

00:48:59.090 --> 00:49:01.580
tend to be highly
motivated people who

00:49:01.580 --> 00:49:04.290
make decisions and move.

00:49:04.290 --> 00:49:06.800
And is it really the
immigration per se,

00:49:06.800 --> 00:49:09.175
or is it those characteristics
of being highly motivated?

00:49:09.175 --> 00:49:10.883
RAJ CHETTY: So this
is a great question--

00:49:10.883 --> 00:49:13.250
gets at kind of the heart
of the statistical issues

00:49:13.250 --> 00:49:15.270
in the paper.

00:49:15.270 --> 00:49:18.110
This is referring to the graph
I showed where the earlier

00:49:18.110 --> 00:49:20.730
you move to Normandy
Park, in that example,

00:49:20.730 --> 00:49:22.400
versus the Central
District, you appear

00:49:22.400 --> 00:49:24.180
to have better
outcomes in adulthood.

00:49:24.180 --> 00:49:26.330
So natural concern
you might have,

00:49:26.330 --> 00:49:28.820
maybe the people who moved
when their kids are younger

00:49:28.820 --> 00:49:30.950
are more motivated,
they're more educated,

00:49:30.950 --> 00:49:32.826
maybe they're different
in various ways.

00:49:32.826 --> 00:49:34.700
That's why their kids
earn more in adulthood,

00:49:34.700 --> 00:49:36.949
not because they're growing
up in Normandy Park-- that

00:49:36.949 --> 00:49:39.380
would be a natural confound
we would worry about.

00:49:39.380 --> 00:49:42.441
Give you a sense of how we can
deal with that kind of issue.

00:49:42.441 --> 00:49:43.940
So with the amount
of data you have,

00:49:43.940 --> 00:49:47.062
you can compare siblings
within the same family.

00:49:47.062 --> 00:49:49.520
So the way we would talk about
that in a regression context

00:49:49.520 --> 00:49:52.970
is put in family fixed effects,
so you're only comparing kids

00:49:52.970 --> 00:49:54.560
within the same family.

00:49:54.560 --> 00:49:56.840
And so effectively what
you're doing there is asking,

00:49:56.840 --> 00:50:00.410
suppose I move to Normandy
Park with a six-year-old

00:50:00.410 --> 00:50:01.690
and a 12-year-old.

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:04.170
I now compare their outcomes.

00:50:04.170 --> 00:50:07.940
What is remarkable is you get
exactly the same chart back

00:50:07.940 --> 00:50:10.410
if you only rely on
within-family comparisons.

00:50:10.410 --> 00:50:12.650
So in other words,
your younger kid

00:50:12.650 --> 00:50:14.900
does better than your
older kid exactly

00:50:14.900 --> 00:50:17.610
in proportion to the age
gap between the two kids.

00:50:17.610 --> 00:50:20.510
So if you think about,
could it be a confound,

00:50:20.510 --> 00:50:22.102
that eliminates a
lot of possibilities

00:50:22.102 --> 00:50:23.685
that it's about
different families who

00:50:23.685 --> 00:50:27.020
are moving when their kids are
young versus old, et cetera.

00:50:27.020 --> 00:50:29.480
And so we do a bunch of other
things along those lines,

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:32.090
including actually studying
a pure randomized experiment

00:50:32.090 --> 00:50:34.520
called the moving to
opportunity experiment, where

00:50:34.520 --> 00:50:36.731
housing vouchers were
randomly assigned,

00:50:36.731 --> 00:50:38.480
and we show you that
you get this pattern.

00:50:38.480 --> 00:50:41.060
So I think we're quite
convinced that this really

00:50:41.060 --> 00:50:42.680
seems to be a causal effect.

00:50:42.680 --> 00:50:43.700
HAL VARIAN: Excellent.

00:50:43.700 --> 00:50:44.504
Jackie.

00:50:44.504 --> 00:50:45.920
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
I'm wondering what

00:50:45.920 --> 00:50:47.840
you think the role is
of government policy

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:50.834
in creating some of these low
opportunity neighborhoods.

00:50:50.834 --> 00:50:52.250
So for example, a
lot of, I think,

00:50:52.250 --> 00:50:54.560
high concentrated
poverty communities

00:50:54.560 --> 00:50:56.450
are housing projects
where government policy

00:50:56.450 --> 00:50:59.480
requires you not
to have two parents

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:03.374
and requires there to be this
high percentage of exactly

00:51:03.374 --> 00:51:04.790
the opposite of
all the things you

00:51:04.790 --> 00:51:07.950
said are important-- low social
capital, and all of that.

00:51:07.950 --> 00:51:14.700
So the role of government
policy and/or market policy--

00:51:14.700 --> 00:51:17.300
for example, redlining districts
and not allowing people to

00:51:17.300 --> 00:51:18.542
move to opportunity.

00:51:18.542 --> 00:51:19.250
RAJ CHETTY: Yeah.

00:51:19.250 --> 00:51:21.860
Yeah, I think
government policies--

00:51:21.860 --> 00:51:25.700
inadvertently perhaps,
and historically perhaps

00:51:25.700 --> 00:51:26.780
by design--

00:51:26.780 --> 00:51:29.480
have led to tremendous
segregation that have basically

00:51:29.480 --> 00:51:31.550
made it hard for people
to access opportunities.

00:51:31.550 --> 00:51:34.550
Let me give you two
concrete examples of that

00:51:34.550 --> 00:51:35.970
that we are thinking about.

00:51:35.970 --> 00:51:39.380
So as I was saying earlier,
we spend $45 billion a year

00:51:39.380 --> 00:51:41.450
on affordable housing in the US.

00:51:41.450 --> 00:51:43.100
You would think the
intention of that

00:51:43.100 --> 00:51:45.440
is to try to provide people
access to housing that will

00:51:45.440 --> 00:51:47.450
give them better opportunities.

00:51:47.450 --> 00:51:50.490
In practice, I
think unfortunately,

00:51:50.490 --> 00:51:52.070
much of that
expenditure is working

00:51:52.070 --> 00:51:53.460
in the opposite direction.

00:51:53.460 --> 00:51:56.336
So I gave you one example with
the housing vouchers, where,

00:51:56.336 --> 00:51:57.710
for whatever
reason, families are

00:51:57.710 --> 00:52:00.620
using these vouchers to live in
pretty low opportunity areas,

00:52:00.620 --> 00:52:04.470
thereby basically exacerbating
the problem of a lack

00:52:04.470 --> 00:52:05.720
of intergenerational mobility.

00:52:05.720 --> 00:52:08.360
A different example of that,
which gets to government policy

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:11.480
design, something called the
Low Income Housing Tax Credit,

00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:13.710
where we spend about
$6 billion a year

00:52:13.710 --> 00:52:17.000
giving developers tax credits
to develop affordable housing.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:18.680
But the way that
program is structured

00:52:18.680 --> 00:52:20.480
is, we give you
bigger incentives

00:52:20.480 --> 00:52:24.320
if you develop housing
in high poverty, what

00:52:24.320 --> 00:52:27.450
end up being relatively
low opportunity areas.

00:52:27.450 --> 00:52:30.580
So we're basically
concentrating poverty further.

00:52:30.580 --> 00:52:33.530
If you overlay where these
light tech developments are

00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:37.620
on our maps, they're all in
very low opportunity places.

00:52:37.620 --> 00:52:40.760
And so I think that is, unless
you think those developments

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:43.230
are going to change the level
of opportunity in that area--

00:52:43.230 --> 00:52:46.230
which is something
one can look into--

00:52:46.230 --> 00:52:48.234
you might actually be
exacerbating the problem

00:52:48.234 --> 00:52:49.650
through the design
of that policy.

00:52:49.650 --> 00:52:52.430
Another example which will
be familiar for folks here

00:52:52.430 --> 00:52:56.820
in Silicon Valley is zoning and
the ability to build housing.

00:52:56.820 --> 00:52:57.470
Right?

00:52:57.470 --> 00:52:59.600
So ultimately, you can
move people around,

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:01.920
but supply is a
fundamental constraint.

00:53:01.920 --> 00:53:04.820
Like, if you can't build any
housing in the Silicon Valley

00:53:04.820 --> 00:53:06.957
area, that's going
to prevent people

00:53:06.957 --> 00:53:09.290
from being able to live in
places where their kids would

00:53:09.290 --> 00:53:11.370
do very well.

00:53:11.370 --> 00:53:13.810
There are serious political
economy problems there,

00:53:13.810 --> 00:53:16.570
where if you already own
a house in Silicon Valley

00:53:16.570 --> 00:53:19.910
you might not want to vote for
more building, and so forth.

00:53:19.910 --> 00:53:22.714
But I think figuring out how
you get around the zoning

00:53:22.714 --> 00:53:24.880
restrictions so you have
more density of development

00:53:24.880 --> 00:53:26.460
and more mixed
income communities

00:53:26.460 --> 00:53:30.225
is another area where
one can have huge impact.

00:53:30.225 --> 00:53:31.600
HAL VARIAN: Let
me-- actually, we

00:53:31.600 --> 00:53:34.990
talked about this first
question here already,

00:53:34.990 --> 00:53:36.070
before the meeting.

00:53:36.070 --> 00:53:37.660
But why don't we go to this one?

00:53:37.660 --> 00:53:41.800
Susan Popkin's research
suggests adverse effects

00:53:41.800 --> 00:53:44.350
for children due to
the disruption that's

00:53:44.350 --> 00:53:46.010
caused by moving.

00:53:46.010 --> 00:53:48.100
RAJ CHETTY: Yeah.

00:53:48.100 --> 00:53:51.610
HAL VARIAN: How do you view that
in terms of this prescription?

00:53:51.610 --> 00:53:55.240
RAJ CHETTY: Yeah, so the way
I would think about the moving

00:53:55.240 --> 00:53:59.200
idea is not that we're going
to uproot families that

00:53:59.200 --> 00:54:01.364
are happily living
in a place and ask

00:54:01.364 --> 00:54:02.530
them to move somewhere else.

00:54:02.530 --> 00:54:04.430
The way this actually
works-- for instance,

00:54:04.430 --> 00:54:07.330
the Seattle experiment I
was describing to you--

00:54:07.330 --> 00:54:10.120
is we take a set
of families that

00:54:10.120 --> 00:54:12.640
have come into the
housing authority,

00:54:12.640 --> 00:54:13.950
they're looking to move.

00:54:13.950 --> 00:54:17.590
20% of low income families
move anyway every year.

00:54:17.590 --> 00:54:20.050
And I think about it as kind
of redirecting the flows.

00:54:20.050 --> 00:54:21.010
You've decided to move.

00:54:21.010 --> 00:54:22.470
You're going to move somewhere.

00:54:22.470 --> 00:54:24.220
Let's give you the
information and support

00:54:24.220 --> 00:54:27.130
to potentially move to a place
where your kids will thrive.

00:54:27.130 --> 00:54:29.525
Not let's go find somebody
who doesn't want to move

00:54:29.525 --> 00:54:30.650
and encourage them to move.

00:54:30.650 --> 00:54:32.980
So that's the way I think
about this issue, kind

00:54:32.980 --> 00:54:33.910
of in a narrow sense.

00:54:33.910 --> 00:54:37.510
But the broader question is, how
can you revitalize communities?

00:54:37.510 --> 00:54:40.449
Which, of course,
is the big issue.

00:54:40.449 --> 00:54:42.490
And some of it, you might
think about the factors

00:54:42.490 --> 00:54:45.700
that I was describing,
related to changing

00:54:45.700 --> 00:54:48.970
the quality of schools, trying
to have better teachers.

00:54:48.970 --> 00:54:51.220
You think about things like
social capital and family

00:54:51.220 --> 00:54:53.220
structure, those things
might be very important,

00:54:53.220 --> 00:54:54.692
but how do we change them?

00:54:54.692 --> 00:54:56.150
That's a really
difficult question.

00:54:56.150 --> 00:54:58.960
So the best I can say there
is, we are trying to now use

00:54:58.960 --> 00:55:01.330
these data to study
various community

00:55:01.330 --> 00:55:04.570
revitalization efforts that have
been conducted over the past 20

00:55:04.570 --> 00:55:07.660
years or so by the government,
by local nonprofits,

00:55:07.660 --> 00:55:09.160
by developers.

00:55:09.160 --> 00:55:11.710
We're building a huge
database of all such efforts

00:55:11.710 --> 00:55:13.240
around the United States.

00:55:13.240 --> 00:55:15.840
And then evaluate, with
this longitudinal data,

00:55:15.840 --> 00:55:18.340
what are the characteristics
of the things that seem to have

00:55:18.340 --> 00:55:20.037
worked and things that haven't?

00:55:20.037 --> 00:55:22.120
And that's our hope of
getting a scientific answer

00:55:22.120 --> 00:55:23.814
to that question.

00:55:23.814 --> 00:55:24.730
HAL VARIAN: Excellent.

00:55:24.730 --> 00:55:27.550
Well, our time is up, but
thank you so much for coming.

00:55:27.550 --> 00:55:29.050
[APPLAUSE]

00:55:29.050 --> 00:55:30.600
RAJ CHETTY: Thank you.

